            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1562236562,
            "creation_date": 1562236562,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n  <p>If I check java.sql.SQLException.venderCode == 1105 will that be enough?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Yes, that vendor code (available by calling <code>getErrorCode()<\/code>) will always map to that error. Just bear in mind it's specific to SQL Server rather than consistent across all SQL implementations.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.sql-server-helper.com/tips/index.aspx\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Various sites like this one<\/a> detail all the error codes available for SQL server (including 1105.)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 56886115,
            "question_id": 56885592
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/7XKVx.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 4571603,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3711162,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3711162/dan-guzman",
                "reputation": 46871,
                "display_name": "Dan Guzman"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1562236765,
            "creation_date": 1562236765,
            "body": "<p>Checking the error code alone is sufficient for your need. The returned <code>vendorCode<\/code> is the SQL Server error number. SQL Server errors and the tokenized message text can be retrieved by the <code>sys.messages<\/code> DMV. Example for the US English language:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM sys.messages\nWHERE\n    message_id = 1105\n    AND language_id = 1033;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 56886184,
            "question_id": 56885592
        }
